Orchestrates the three top-level CTX scan operations — full scan, staleness check, and incremental update — by composing `ctx-summarize`'s walk/summarize primitives with this crate's hash tree and README writer. All three entry points (`scan_run`, `check_run`, `update_run`) construct a `StdFs` rooted at `base` and are the outer API other crates call; `summarize` is the inner, `Fs`/`Agent`-generic step meant for direct use with fakes in tests.

Non-obvious: prompts are always loaded from `prompts_dir` resolved against the process cwd (`load_prompts`), never against `base` — the scan target doesn't need to carry CTX's own prompt files. `update_run` short-circuits to `Ok(stale)` before loading prompts or touching the filesystem if `stale.is_fresh()`, so a fresh tree does zero model calls and zero writes (including no README rewrite). `regenerate` processes `stale.changed_files` (leaf resummarize), then `orphan_leaves` (removal), then `stale_dirs` (rollups) — relies on `Staleness.stale_dirs` already being ordered deepest-first by `hash::diff`; reordering would break rollups that read child summaries before they're regenerated.

Coupling: depends on `hash::compute`/`diff`/`load_stored`/`store`/`record_missing_artifacts` for staleness semantics, and on `summ::scope_check` for the approval-gate behavior shared with plain summarize — changes to either module's staleness model or scope-check signature ripple here directly.

Invariant: `scan_run` and `update_run` (non-fresh path) always call `hash::store` after successful summarization, keeping the sidecar hash tree in sync with what was actually written; `check_run` never writes anything.